00:16:06.390 --> 00:16:09.840
Ten years ago, when my son was
five, he came over to me with

00:16:09.840 --> 00:16:12.300
a very confused look
on his face.

00:16:12.300 --> 00:16:14.720
He'd grown up with my work on
the ENIAC programmers, and

00:16:14.720 --> 00:16:17.000
he'd even met and actually
played with four of the

00:16:17.000 --> 00:16:19.230
original six ENIAC
programmers.

00:16:19.230 --> 00:16:22.850
And he looked upset/ and he
said, mom, I know that women

00:16:22.850 --> 00:16:25.110
can be computer programmers,
but can men be

00:16:25.110 --> 00:16:26.360
programmers, too?

00:16:28.830 --> 00:16:31.960
I assured him that, of course,
women and men could be

00:16:31.960 --> 00:16:35.190
programmers, and in fact,
technology was better when we

00:16:35.190 --> 00:16:36.240
created it together.

00:16:36.240 --> 00:16:39.570
And when I left him two nights
ago, he was programming.

00:16:39.570 --> 00:16:43.610
